Gift Opportunities

Scholarships / Research / Professorships / Centers of Excellence / Capital Projects / Athletic Support

 
 
 
 
 
 
 
  


Endowed Scholarships

More than ever before, scholarships are opening doors and enabling talented students with demonstrated financial need to realize their dreams of a Marist education.

Approximately 85% of Marist undergraduate students receive some financial assistance. It is estimated that more than half of all current Marist students are employed on campus or hold part-time jobs while attending school.

An endowed scholarship fund yields support that benefits students annually. By establishing such a fund, the donor can make a contribution to the future of Marist College that will stand in perpetuity.

The College’s participation in the American Talent Initiative (ATI), announced in 2017, will bolster Marist’s efforts to increase access for talented low- and moderate-income students. ATI brings top colleges and universities together with the philanthropy and research communities to expand access and opportunity for these students. By 2025, ATI aims to attract, enroll, and graduate an additional 50,000 lower-income students at the 296 colleges and universities that consistently graduate at least 70 percent of their students in six years. ATI members are a subset of these 296 and include a mix of public and private institutions all over the country including some of the country’s most prestigious schools such as Harvard, Yale, Princeton, and Stanford. 

 

Students collect samples aboard Marist’s research vessel on the Hudson River.

Endowed Research Funds

Some of the most powerful learning experiences come not in the classroom, but in the lab or out in the field, where students and faculty work together on new research. At Marist, students have the opportunity to work directly with faculty members who are leaders in their fields, conducting important research that advances knowledge in their respective disciplines while furthering their education. 

To become increasingly competitive with Marist’s aspirant peers, attract and retain the most sought-after student and faculty scholars, and provide the most powerful learning experiences available, Marist is actively seeking to establish new endowed undergraduate research funds in each of its six traditional academic schools. This funding will provide the resources needed for laboratory study and experimentation, travel, conference participation, faculty release time, and stipends for summer study.

 

Dr. James M. Johnson, the Dr. Frank T. Bumpus Chair in Hudson River Valley History, teaches a class during spring 2018. 

 

Professorships and Faculty Chairs 

Today, the world’s best colleges and universities benefit richly from the presence of endowed chairs and professorships that create a sustainable source of support for select faculty positions. These prestigious faculty positions can be invaluable in recruiting and retaining both highly accomplished faculty members and rising stars in targeted disciplines. Such faculty luminaries conduct groundbreaking research, publish their findings in respected scholarly journals, and are frequently cited in local and national media outlets for their highly specialized expertise, helping to further position Marist as a nationally recognized leader in multiple academic disciplines. Most importantly, through their exemplary leadership they serve as an invaluable resource for students on a wide range of academic and co-curricular initiatives. New chairs for senior-level faculty and professorships for rising faculty stars are being sought in all disciplines.

 

 

More than 300 student interviewers and supervisors have a front-row seat on the political process as they carry out surveys for the Marist College Institute of Public Opinion.

Centers of Excellence

As Marist continues to draw talented students and exceptional teacher–scholars, opportunities exist to match their collective knowledge with the appropriate resources and focus both within new centers of excellence. Hallmarks of these centers are nationally recognized expertise; faculty and student research; and work that is shared for the public good. As Marist looks to establish these centers in each of the College’s seven schools, the nationally prominent Marist College Institute for Public Opinion and Hudson River Valley Institute, along with the Raymond A. Rich Institute for Leadership Development, Investment Center, Center for Sports Communication, Center for Civic Engagement and Leadership, and the IDEA Center, are the standard-bearers. Support for these centers of focused teaching, learning, and research will enable the continued advancement of important areas of study.

On Sept. 12, 2018, Marist and Health Quest announced a pioneering collaboration that will change the academic and healthcare landscape by training the next generation of physicians who are so crucial to the future of healthcare. The Marist Health Quest School of Medicine aspires to become a nationally recognized leader in technology-enabled medical education. This unique partnership will push the boundaries of healthcare by focusing on where medicine is going, not where it has been. Through the use of Marist’s advanced learning management systems and the addition of artificial intelligence, Marist and Health Quest will transform the traditional medical school model, ultimately leading to physicians better prepared for the future. 


The Marist Health Quest School of Medicine will provide major benefits to both the College and the Hudson Valley. With only 151 MD-granting medical schools in the country, Marist is set to join an exclusive academic, research, and clinical community.  Its already strong and growing science programs will greatly benefit from the addition of a medical school. An academic medical center will attract a highly accomplished population of medical students, residents, and clinical faculty, many of whom will remain in the Hudson Valley. Local community members will enjoy increased access to top-quality healthcare close to home. Finally, the medical school will bring economic benefits to the region in the form of more than 100 full-time jobs and numerous additional part-time opportunities.  

The College is actively seeking philanthropic support from individuals, foundations, and corporations to help attract and retain top-notch faculty; establish scholarships that will enable recruitment of the most talented, diverse students possible; and support leading-edge research. Gifts will also be instrumental in ensuring that facilities and technological resources are truly state of the art and reflective of the innovative, forward-thinking philosophy upon which the Marist Health Quest School of Medicine will be built.  

Capital Projects

The Steel Plant Studios


The Steel Plant Studios complex is an extraordinary learning center for the Fashion Program and the Department of Art and Digital Media.

One of the world’s premier architectural firms has transformed the Steel Plant Studios into an extraordinary learning center for the Fashion Program and the Department of Art and Digital Media. High ceilings and high tech are the hallmarks of this project designed by Robert A. M. Stern Architects, incorporating brick, steel, polished concrete, terrazzo, corrugated metal, tile, and wood to achieve a “Hudson River Valley” industrial–modern style.

The renovation has added 35,000 square feet of much-needed space including galleries, classrooms, and digital labs. Space for the Fashion Program more than doubled when the program moved into the Steel Plant. 

The Steel Plant Studios offer a number of creative naming opportunities, including the building itself. The Mporium, the highly successful boutique and entrepreneurship lab operated by merchandising students in the Fashion Program, occupies a high-visibility spot at the Steel Plant entrance. The stunning winter garden is an airy indoor space featuring a café, seating, and lush greenery. World-class galleries showcase the work of both Art and Fashion students and serve as expansive venues for openings, parties, and other events. Maker spaces offer students the tools to give their ideas texture, form, and dimension, inspiring experimentation and invention. Classrooms and labs provide cutting-edge technology that will prepare Fashion and Art students for the professional world beyond college. A curated archive, critical to fashion education, engages students in the study of clothing as it relates to social and historical movements and draws researchers to the campus. 

 

 

The James J. McCann Recreation Center

The renovation and expansion of the McCann Center will increase the College’s capacity to meet the fitness and recreational needs of all students.

The James J. McCann Charitable Trust recently issued a $2 million grant to support the significant renovation and expansion of the James J. McCann Recreation Center. The center is not only the home of the Red Foxes but also a hub for intramural and club sports, wellness pursuits, and social and academic events for all students. It is also a premier venue for activities and events open to the general public. The James J. McCann Charitable Trust played a key role in the original construction of the McCann Center in 1977 and has supported each major renovation and addition to this important campus facility over the past 40 years. The project now underway will increase the College’s capacity to meet the fitness and recreational needs of all students and offers a number of exciting naming opportunities.


New features within the McCann Center will include a nearly 8,000-square-foot weight room for varsity athletes, with a refueling station and multiple lane 40-yard turf track; a 7,600-square-foot fitness center for all students, with treatment space for a new partnership with the College’s Doctor of Physical Therapy Program; two full-size basketball courts for intramural and club sports; a second-story walking track; multipurpose space with an indoor turf area; and multipurpose rooms with hardwood floors for fitness, dance, yoga, and academic classes.


A highlight of the project will be an ESPN teaching control room for training students for professional opportunities in live production through a partnership with Marist’s Center for Sports Communication. Plans also call for renovated locker room space to accommodate varsity student-athletes with team rooms and shared lounges and a renovated athletic training room/tape room to include new carpeting and training tables.


Fans of the Red Foxes will enjoy an apparel shop, a café/lounge with space for concessions on arena game days, and an expanded ticket office with multiple box office windows for will-call and ticket sales on game days and throughout the year.

 

Athletic Support

Marist is proud to offer 24 Division I sports, as well as the opportunity for students to participate in a wide range of club, intramural, and recreational athletic activities.  The Athletics Program aims to complement academic and social experiences with the development of organizational skills, leadership qualities, and an appreciation for sportsmanship. Teams rely heavily on the generosity of alumni, parents, and friends to provide much needed annual operating support, as well as endowed funds, that help the Red Foxes remain competitive and offer the best possible experiences and opportunities for student athletes.
